\subsection{Universe-bump and full cover-totality bridge (iter-034)}

Iter-031 / iter-032 / iter-033 supplied the three pieces of the \emph{cover-totality} identification: a sheaf-level natural iso (iter-031), an Ext-transport at universe $u{+}1$ (iter-032, landing on $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$), and a parallel Ext-transport at universe $u$ (iter-033, landing on $\Ext_u\,X_2\,F\,n$ for $X_2 = (\constantSheaf\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k)$). What remains to obtain the \emph{full bridge} $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ is the \emph{universe bump} $\Ext_u\,X_2\,F\,n \equiv_{\Module k} \Ext_{u+1}\,X_2\,F\,n$, since $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ is by definition (iter-009) $\Ext_{u+1}\,X_2\,F\,n$.

Mathlib provides $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUniv} : \Ext_w\,X\,Y\,n \cong \Ext_{w'}\,X\,Y\,n$ (file \texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/Basic.lean} L540) as a bare $\Equiv$, built on $\mathtt{SmallShiftedHom.chgUniv}$ in a way that preserves the underlying derived-category morphism (witnessed by the load-bearing intermediate lemma $\Ext.\mathtt{homEquiv\_chgUniv}$ at L543–545). Combined with $\Ext.\mathtt{add\_hom}$ (L364) and $\Ext.\mathtt{smul\_hom}$ (\texttt{Ext/Linear.lean} L52), the underlying-morphism preservation forces additivity and $R$-linearity: the $\AddCommGroup$ and $\Module R$ structures on $\Ext$ are themselves transferred from the standard derived category through $\mathtt{homEquiv}$ (L241–243 / L39–41), so any operation that commutes with $\mathtt{homEquiv}$ commutes with $+$ and $\bullet$.

\begin{definition}[Universe-bump $\LinearEquiv$ — Mathlib gap-fill, iter-034]
  \label{def:Abelian_Ext_chgUnivLinearEquiv}
  \lean{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.chgUnivLinearEquiv}
  \uses{}
  \leanok
  Let $R$ be a ring, $C$ an $R$-linear abelian category, and $w, w'$ universes such that $\HasExt_w\,C$ and $\HasExt_{w'}\,C$. There is an $R$-linear isomorphism
  \[
    \Ext_w\,X\,Y\,n
    \;\equiv_{\Module R}\;
    \Ext_{w'}\,X\,Y\,n.
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  The underlying bijection is Mathlib's $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUniv}$. To prove additivity, fix the standard derived-category instance $\mathtt{HasDerivedCategory.standard}\,C$ and apply $\Ext.\mathtt{ext}$ (homomorphism injectivity through $\mathtt{homEquiv}$). The goal becomes $\mathtt{homEquiv}\,(\mathtt{chgUniv}\,(a+b)) = \mathtt{homEquiv}\,(\mathtt{chgUniv}\,a) + \mathtt{homEquiv}\,(\mathtt{chgUniv}\,b)$; using $\Ext.\mathtt{add\_hom}$ on both sides reduces to $\mathtt{homEquiv}\,(\mathtt{chgUniv}\,(a+b)) = \mathtt{homEquiv}\,(a+b)$ (and similarly for the summands), which is exactly $\Ext.\mathtt{homEquiv\_chgUniv}$ applied three times. The $R$-linearity proof is identical with $\Ext.\mathtt{smul\_hom}$ in place of $\Ext.\mathtt{add\_hom}$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-034 pass) confirms both helper lemmas plus the bundled $\LinearEquiv$ structure literal typecheck end-to-end and produce kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\begin{definition}[Full cover-totality bridge $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ for terminal $T$, iter-034]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_eq_HModule_linearEquiv}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_eq_HModule_linearEquiv}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_top_linearEquiv, def:Abelian_Ext_chgUnivLinearEquiv, def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
  \leanok
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category with morphism universe $u$, $J : \GrothendieckTopology\,C$, $T : C$ a terminal object, and assume $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\Type\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, $\HasExt_u\,(\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$, and $\HasExt_{u+1}\,(\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$. There is a $k$-linear isomorphism
  \[
    \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T
    \;\equiv_{\Module k}\;
    \HModule\,k\,F\,n.
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  Compose iter-033's $\HModulePrimeTopLinearEquiv$ (which lands on $\Ext_u\,X_2\,F\,n$ for $X_2 = (\constantSheaf\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k)$) with the universe-bump $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUnivLinearEquiv}$ from Definition~\ref{def:Abelian_Ext_chgUnivLinearEquiv} (which lifts $\Ext_u\,X_2\,F\,n$ to $\Ext_{u+1}\,X_2\,F\,n$). By definition (iter-009), $\HModule\,k\,F\,n = \Ext_{u+1}\,X_2\,F\,n$, so the composition yields the desired $\LinearEquiv$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-034 pass) confirms the one-liner $(\HModulePrimeTopLinearEquiv\,k\,F\,n\,h_T).\mathtt{trans}\,\Ext.\mathtt{chgUnivLinearEquiv}$ typechecks and produces kernel-only axioms. Both $\HasExt_u$ and $\HasExt_{u+1}$ must be passed as explicit hypotheses (typeclass synthesis from $\HasSheafify$ alone times out on the underlying $\HasSmallLocalizedHom$ chain at 20\,000 heartbeats).
\end{proof}

\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}

The iter-029 lemmas materialise Step 1 (the abstract LES) and Step 2 (the corner-identification simp lemmas) of the iter-028 Serre-finiteness sketch (Section~\ref{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare}); iter-030 materialised Step 2.5 (the toModuleKSheaf specialisation, a routine binding so downstream code paths can reference the LES on the structure sheaf of a curve directly); iter-031 materialised the \emph{source-object} half of Step 3 (the cover-totality identification at the sheaf level); iter-032 materialised the \emph{Ext-transport} half of Step 3 at universe $u+1$ (landing on $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$); iter-033 materialised the parallel \emph{Ext-transport} at universe $u$ (landing on $\Ext_u\,X_2\,F\,n$); iter-034 (this iteration) closes Step 3 by appending the Mathlib gap-fill $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUnivLinearEquiv}$ (universe-bump $\LinearEquiv$ upgrade of Mathlib's bare $\Equiv$ $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUniv}$) and composing iter-033 with it to produce the full bridge $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ for terminal $T$. The remaining work — Step 4 (affine vanishing $H^{>0}(\Spec A, \mathcal F) = 0$, possibly multi-iteration depending on Mathlib state) and Step 5 (finiteness of each $H^0$ piece, hence of $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$) — is iter-035+. The intermediate iter-035 step (specialise to $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ via iter-029's $\mathtt{toMayerVietorisSquare\_toSquare\_X_4} : \ldots = \top$ simp lemma to land the bridge on the $X_4$ corner of an affine cover) is plausibly single-iteration $\sim$10–20 LOC.

